stylometry: At risk output allows you to see the profit associated with the model you performed.  You have to make sure profit is an output cell so the profit can be determined.  Some of the things the @risk shows is the number of calendars you order.  It then shows the expected demand and how if there are any holding costs associated with extra inventory.  If there are it calculates it.  If you are able to see back calendars or shoes to the company if you dont sell them the@risk will also perform this function and calculate a profit.   When all of these things are done it will then give you the profit.  The risks associated with purchasing a high inventory or low demand or interpreted to you based on the output cell which is the profit.
